description:
## Severity
Major

## Dimension
DRY / Decoupling

## Location
src/tools/file/write.rs:19-34 vs src/tools/file/edit.rs:19-40 vs src/tools/file/notebook.rs:99-108 (canonicalize-or-walk-parent dance)

## Violation
Three near-identical blocks each implement "canonicalize the path, and if the file does not yet exist, canonicalize its parent and rejoin the filename":

write.rs:
```rust
let canonical = match std::fs::canonicalize(&p) {
    Ok(canon) => canon,
    Err(_) => {
        if let Some(parent) = p.parent() {
            std::fs::canonicalize(parent).map_or_else(
                |_| p.clone(),
                |canon_parent| canon_parent.join(p.file_name().unwrap_or_default()),
            )
        } else { return (format!("Invalid path: '{path}'"), true); }
    }
};
```

edit.rs:19-40 implements the same pattern but errors when the parent doesn't exist (different behavior!).
notebook.rs:99-108 implements yet another variant that errors on any canonicalize failure (different behavior!).

Three subtly different copies of the same logic. The mod.rs::resolve_path function already does this exact thing in lines 144-164 — but the three tools re-implement it instead of just calling resolve_path. Worse, each gets the divergent error behavior wrong in a different way.

## Mandated refactor
Delete the three duplicate blocks. resolve_path is already canonical; the tools should rely on its output. The post-resolve_path re-canonicalize was added (per the inline comments) "to prevent symlink-based path traversal" — but resolve_path ALREADY does that. The duplication exists only because the original tools were written before resolve_path was hardened.

